---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

// Tenant-mix comparison (Finding 5) rendered as an accessible table.
const mixRows: { measure: string; south: string; east: string }[] = [
  { measure: 'Retail goods', south: '41%', east: '21%' },
  { measure: 'Professional services', south: '1%', east: '11%' },
  { measure: 'Health and fitness', south: '6%', east: '8%' },
  { measure: 'Grocery and fresh food', south: '3%', east: '5%' },
  { measure: 'Takeout / quick-service restaurants (count)', south: '19', east: '6' },
  { measure: 'Peaks late at night', south: '23%', east: 'under 1%' },
  { measure: 'Smoke shops and check-cashers', south: '9%', east: '0%' },
  { measure: 'Outdoor seating', south: '7%', east: '20%' },
];

// Jump-link table of contents.
const toc: { id: string; title: string }[] = [
  { id: 'finding-1', title: 'The occupancy gap' },
  { id: 'finding-2', title: 'A zoning patchwork on one corridor' },
  { id: 'finding-3', title: 'Dormant ownership and the land-value decoupling' },
  { id: 'finding-4', title: 'Decay in motion' },
  { id: 'finding-5', title: 'The mix flipped, not the ownership' },
  { id: 'finding-6', title: 'The damage concentrates on a few blocks' },
];
---

<Layout title="Findings · Saving South Street">
  <div class="finding-wrap">
    <!-- HERO -->
    <section>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">Findings</h1>
      <p class="finding-headline">South Street's decline is structural, not ambient.</p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-stone-700">
        A 2026 field survey of every storefront on the corridor, measured against East Passyunk
        Avenue.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm">
        <a
          href="/thesis.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="text-stone-500 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-stone-800"
        >Read the full chapter (PDF)</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">Executive summary</h2>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's emptiness gets blamed on COVID and e-commerce. This study tests that with a
        2026 field survey of every storefront on the corridor, measured against East Passyunk Avenue,
        a peer with the same pre-1900 building stock, the same density and transit, and a
        wealthier-than-average neighborhood. East Passyunk faced the same retail pressure and stayed
        full. South Street did not. The decline is structural to the corridor, not ambient to retail.
      </p>
      <ul class="finding-stats">
        <li><strong>A 17-point occupancy gap.</strong> South Street runs 70.3% occupied against East Passyunk's 87.3%.</li>
        <li><strong>Half the vacancy is frozen.</strong> Of 68 empty storefronts, 35 are long-term vacant, against just 2 on East Passyunk. The emptiness is stuck, not turning over.</li>
        <li><strong>A zoning patchwork.</strong> South Street splits into 3 districts across 4 CMX classes plus residential pockets, while East Passyunk runs on a single designation, so the same use can be by-right at one address and need a variance a few doors down.</li>
        <li><strong>3 in 5 parcels sit with dormant owners.</strong> 155 of 271 parcels have either changed hands without a market sale or not sold in over 20 years.</li>
        <li><strong>Prices climb while the buildings rot.</strong> South Street land sells for about 1.8x East Passyunk's, a $273,000 premium, even as half its parcels logged a new code violation in the last 3 years, 4x East Passyunk's count.</li>
        <li><strong>The mix flipped, not the ownership.</strong> Both corridors are about 87% independent, so chains are a myth. South Street skews value-priced, late-night, and takeout, with smoke shops and check-cashers at 9.4% of tenants versus zero, and it runs thin on daytime, fitness, and fresh-food uses.</li>
        <li><strong>The culture economy hollowed out.</strong> The corridor that ran on live music, comedy, and galleries is down to one surviving venue, the TLA. The Laff House, where Kevin Hart and Bill Burr started, closed in 2013 with no comedy club since, and a third of the corridor's anchor parcels, several of them former venues, sit empty.</li>
        <li><strong>The damage concentrates on a few blocks.</strong> The Front-to-5th dead zone carries the worst of it. The 300 block alone is 59% vacant, while the western 900 and 1000 blocks outperform East Passyunk.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- ON THIS PAGE -->
    <nav class="finding-toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <span class="finding-toc-label">On this page</span>
      <ol class="finding-toc-list">
        {toc.map((item, i) => (
          <li>
            <a href={`#${item.id}`}><span class="finding-toc-num">{i + 1}</span> {item.title}</a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <!-- FINDING 1 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-1">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 1</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">The occupancy gap</h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">70.3%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">South Street occupied</span>
          </div>
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">87.3%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">East Passyunk occupied</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">a 17-point gap</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        East Passyunk sits on the same pre-1900 building stock, the same density, and the same
        transit, and it faced the same retail pressure. It stayed full. South Street did not.
      </p>
      <blockquote class="finding-quote">
        <p>South Street is a shell of its former self.</p>
        <cite>Corridor stakeholder, 2026 interviews</cite>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="finding-body">
        The headline is the 17-point gap. The deeper finding is the composition of that vacancy, and
        it is the more important of the two. South Street has 68 vacant storefronts and 35 of them
        are long-term vacant. East Passyunk has 20 vacant and only 2 are long-term. Half of South
        Street's vacancy is sitting still.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        A storefront counts as long-term vacant when it shows no for-rent signage, no posted permits,
        no construction visible through the windows, and visible signs of accumulated neglect like
        rotted trim, leaks, layered trash, and graffiti that has faded from age. In plainer terms,
        the test is whether the space could realistically appear on a commercial brokerage listing
        today. If it could not, it qualifies.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.6.webp"
          alt="Bar chart comparing commercial occupancy rates: South Street 70.3 percent, East Passyunk 87.3 percent."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.6. Commercial occupancy rate on South Street and East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            Commercial occupancy on South Street trails East Passyunk by 17 percentage points, with
            70.3% of commercial real estate space active compared to 87.3% on East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Sample restricted to parcels with commercial real
            estate space, meaning a parcel with an active business or a labeled commercial vacancy
            (South Street n=229; East Passyunk n=157). Residential parcels on CMX zoning are excluded.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.7.webp"
          alt="Chart comparing vacancy type composition on South Street and East Passyunk, showing South Street's larger share of long-term vacancy."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.7. Vacancy type composition on South Street and East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            South Street has 35 long-term commercial vacancies compared to East Passyunk's 2. East
            Passyunk's vacancies skew toward short-term turnover.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Sample restricted to vacant commercial parcels
            (South Street n=68; East Passyunk n=20). Vacancy type assigned during the field survey
            based on observed conditions, signage, and permit activity.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 2 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-2">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 2</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        A zoning patchwork on one corridor
      </h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">3</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">zoning districts across 4 CMX classes</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">East Passyunk runs on 1</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        From the sidewalk the two corridors look alike, brick row buildings 2 to 4 stories tall with
        retail below and apartments above. The difference shows up in the zoning. East Passyunk's
        architectural evenness mirrors its single designation.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's CMX patchwork sorts geographically like a field goal post. CMX-3 and CMX-2.5
        cluster on the eastern blocks between 2nd and 5th and the western blocks between 9th and 11th,
        while the middle runs lighter on CMX-1 and CMX-2 with residential pockets on the 100, 700, and
        800 blocks. The net result is 3 distinct districts embedded within an 11-block corridor.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        A tenant looking at two storefronts a few doors apart can find one that permits the business
        by-right and another that routes the same use through the Zoning Board for a variance. That
        friction shapes what can open where.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.2.webp"
          alt="Chart of the base zoning composition of South Street and East Passyunk parcels by CMX classification."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.2. Base zoning composition of South Street and East Passyunk parcels.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            South Street's parcels span four CMX classifications and a residential pocket, while East
            Passyunk runs on a single CMX-2.5 designation.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's analysis of Philadelphia City Planning Commission zoning records,
            accessed May 2026.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 3 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-3">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 3</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        Dormant ownership and the land-value decoupling
      </h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">1.8x</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">land price vs East Passyunk</span>
          </div>
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">$273K</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">price premium</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">3 in 5 parcels held by dormant owners</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        A commercial parcel carries two kinds of value, the land underneath and the building on top.
        When ownership is engaged, operating the storefront, collecting rent, and maintaining the
        asset, both kinds of value rise together. When ownership is dormant, holding for land
        appreciation rather than operating income, the two decouple. The land keeps appreciating on
        location and redevelopment potential. The building deteriorates because no one is maintaining
        it.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        That decoupling is South Street's diagnosis. High parcel prices coexist with deteriorating
        buildings because the corridor's dormant owners profit from holding without operating, and
        still draw cashflow from the apartment units above.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        The price floor comes from the neighbors. South Street runs between Society Hill and Queen
        Village, two of the highest-income residential neighborhoods in Philadelphia, and sits a
        15-minute walk from Center City. Those neighborhoods price the corridor's land independently
        of how the commercial use performs, because a dormant storefront still sits on a parcel the
        residential market values highly. East Passyunk had no such price floor when PARC and its
        predecessor began assembling property, which let them acquire 10 parcels and tie rents to
        tenant sales. South Street never had a group buy the bricks. Its long holds belong to
        portfolio owners like Michael Axelrod, who began assembling parcels in 1985, and Midwood
        Investment &amp; Development, which acquired 11 of them in 2016. Together they control more
        than 40 addresses, concentrated on the eastern blocks where vacancy runs heaviest.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.4.webp"
          alt="Box plot of the distribution of years since last sale for South Street and East Passyunk parcels."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.4. Distribution of years since last sale on South Street and East Passyunk
            parcels, 2025.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            South Street's ownership turnover is similar to East Passyunk's at the median, but its
            upper quartile and right tail run noticeably longer, with 34.9% of South Street CMX
            parcels last sold 20 or more years ago compared with 22.4% on East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's analysis of Philadelphia Office of Property Assessment records. Sample
            restricted to CMX-zoned parcels with valid sale date records (South Street n=235 of 245;
            East Passyunk n=196 of 196). Box edges mark the first and third quartiles; the median
            divides the lighter and darker halves of each box.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 4 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-4">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 4</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">Decay in motion</h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">50.2%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">of CMX parcels with a new violation in 3 years</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">4x East Passyunk's rate</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        This is the building half of the decoupling. The violation profile is not residue from a past
        decade. The deterioration is happening in motion, while price speculation remains high. South
        Street's violation profile exceeds East Passyunk's at every threshold, and 16.2% of its
        parcels carry open violations today. Owners are not investing in the buildings even as the
        parcels appreciate.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.5.webp"
          alt="Chart of code violation severity and recent activity for South Street and East Passyunk parcels."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.5. Code violation severity and recent activity on South Street and East Passyunk
            parcels.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            South Street's violation profile exceeds East Passyunk's at every threshold, and 50.2% of
            South Street CMX parcels recorded a new violation in the last three years compared to
            17.3% on East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's analysis of Philadelphia Office of Property Assessment records and
            Licenses &amp; Inspections violation history. Sample restricted to CMX-zoned parcels
            (South Street n=245; East Passyunk n=196). The "Recent" bar reflects parcels with a most
            recent violation date on or after January 1, 2023.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 5 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-5">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 5</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        The mix flipped, not the ownership
      </h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">86%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">South Street independent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">88%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">East Passyunk independent</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">chains are a myth, the mix is what changed</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        Interviewees on both corridors voiced a common claim that South Street lost its character to
        national chains. The data does not bear that out. Both corridors are independent-dominated,
        with 86.2% of South Street's tenants and 87.9% of East Passyunk's operating as single-location
        independents. Independence is not the variable that diverged.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        What diverged is the composition of that independent base. South Street is more than twice as
        concentrated in retail goods (41.3% vs 20.5%) and under-concentrated in the categories that
        anchor a daily-life corridor. Same shell, different commercial economy. Smoke shops and
        alternative financial services account for 9.4% of South Street's active tenants and zero of
        East Passyunk's. Its food and drink also leans takeout: 19 quick-service spots against 10
        full-service, while East Passyunk runs the reverse at 25 full-service to 6 quick-service.
      </p>

      <div class="finding-table-wrap">
        <table class="finding-table">
          <caption class="finding-table-caption">
            Tenant mix on South Street compared with East Passyunk.
          </caption>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Measure</th>
              <th scope="col">South Street</th>
              <th scope="col">East Passyunk</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {mixRows.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">{row.measure}</th>
                <td>{row.south}</td>
                <td>{row.east}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-source finding-source--table">
        Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Active CMX tenants (South Street n=160; East Passyunk
        n=132).
      </p>

      <p class="finding-body">
        Nearly 1 in 4 South Street tenants (23.1%) peaks during late-night hours, compared to less
        than 1% on East Passyunk, which concentrates 79.5% of its tenants in the afternoon and
        evening, the hours that serve a neighborhood. Sidewalk seating turns a visit into a stay: a
        diner at a sidewalk table holds the storefront for 90 minutes instead of 9. South Street's mix
        produces faster, in-and-out visits. The mid-day to early-evening economy is what is missing.
        One director at a large Philadelphia brokerage admitted they no longer send tenants to scout
        South Street at all, a measure of how far the gap has opened.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 6 -->
    <section class="finding-section" id="finding-6">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 6</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        The damage concentrates on a few blocks
      </h2>
      <div class="finding-statblock">
        <div class="finding-stat-items">
          <div class="finding-stat-item">
            <span class="finding-stat-num">59%</span>
            <span class="finding-stat-label">vacancy on the 300 block</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="finding-stat-sub">double the 30% corridor average</p>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's 30% corridor average is propped up almost entirely by the 300 block. Remove it
        and the remaining 10 blocks come in at 24%, 6 points lower. The 900 and 1000 blocks at 11.5%
        outperform East Passyunk's corridor-wide rate of 12.7%, which means the healthy end of South
        Street is healthier than the comparison corridor. The 300 block alone holds 14 of South
        Street's 35 long-term vacant parcels, 40% of the corridor's stuck inventory on a single block.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.8.webp"
          alt="Bar chart of commercial vacancy rate by block on South Street, with the 300 block as a clear outlier."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-fig-title">
            Figure 5.8. Commercial vacancy rate by block on South Street, 2026.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-fig-subtitle">
            The 300 block carries 23 vacant parcels out of 39 (59%), more than the next three
            worst-performing blocks combined and roughly double the South Street corridor average of
            30%.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's 2026 field survey. Vacancy rate per block calculated as the share of
            commercial parcels currently vacant. Sample includes all South Street parcels with
            commercial real estate space (n=229). The 300 block is highlighted as the corridor's
            vacancy outlier.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <blockquote class="finding-quote">
        <p>A ghost town.</p>
        <cite>Interviewee describing the Front-to-5th blocks</cite>
      </blockquote>

      <aside class="finding-callout">
        <img
          class="finding-callout-img"
          src="/images/tla-marquee.png"
          alt="The Theatre of the Living Arts marquee on South Street, the corridor's last surviving live venue."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <div class="finding-callout-body">
          <h3 class="finding-callout-title">The dead zone is where the culture used to be.</h3>
          <p>
            The Front-to-5th stretch that one interviewee called a ghost town is the same ground that
            once held the corridor's live entertainment cluster, with live music, jazz, and comedy
            clubs. South Street built its name on that scene.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today it is down to one surviving live anchor, the Theatre of the Living Arts. Ripley's
            Music Hall closed in 1985, Grendel's Lair in 1987, and JC Dobbs in 1996. The Laff House,
            where Kevin Hart and Bill Burr started out, closed in 2013, and no comedy club has
            replaced it in the 13 years since.
          </p>
          <p>
            By the 2026 survey, arts and culture had fallen to 4.4% of the corridor's active tenants,
            a steep drop for a street that once ran on performance. A third of South Street's anchor
            parcels, 9 of 27, sit empty, several of them former venues.
          </p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <!-- HANDOFF -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-handoff-lead">
        These findings are the evidence. What they mean, and what to do about them, lives on the next
        two tabs.
      </p>
      <ul class="finding-handoff-list">
        <li>
          <a href="/analysis">The Policy Analysis tab</a> traces the three problems behind the numbers
          and lays out four proposals.
        </li>
        <li><a href="/map">The Map</a> shows the survey parcel by parcel.</li>
        <li>
          The full Chapter V, with every figure and table, is in the
          <a href="/thesis.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">thesis</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* One column: the Layout <main> already centers at max-w-6xl with px-6, so the
     content fills that single width. No inner measure cap, so prose, bullets,
     figures, and the table all share the same width. */

  /* Headline under the H1. */
  .finding-headline {
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
    font-size: 1.65rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    color: #1c1917; /* stone-900 */
  }

  /* Section rhythm: a thin rule sets each section apart, like the History page. */
  .finding-section {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e7e5e4; /* stone-200 */
  }

  .finding-kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.2rem;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: #78716c; /* stone-500 */
  }

  .finding-body {
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    color: #44403c; /* stone-700 */
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  /* Executive-summary stat bullets: bold lead, regular after. */
  .finding-stats {
    margin: 1.2rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .finding-stats li {
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 1.1rem;
    color: #44403c; /* stone-700 */
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .finding-stats li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.6em;
    width: 5px;
    height: 5px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: #a8a29e; /* stone-400 */
  }
  .finding-stats li strong {
    color: #1c1917; /* stone-900 */
  }

  /* On-this-page jump-link nav. */
  .finding-toc {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid #e7e5e4; /* stone-200 */
  }
  .finding-toc-label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
